      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why T-Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>T's six tiles in the bag make it one of the most common consonants you'll draw. While it scores just 1 point on its own, T's value comes from being the starting letter of thousands of common English words. It pairs naturally with virtually every vowel and consonant, forming the TH digraph (the most common two-letter combination in English), TR- and ST- clusters, and productive prefixes like TRI- and TRANS-.</p>
      <p>In competitive play, T is a "glue" tile — it connects rack fragments into complete words. A rack with T, common vowels, and one high-value tile (X, Z, or J) almost always has a playable word. That reliability is T's true strength.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing T-Words</h2>
      <p>T is about consistent scoring and enabling better plays. Here's how to get the most from your T tiles:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>T+X power plays:</strong> TAX and TUX both score 10 points for 3 letters. TAXICAB (18 pts), TEXTBOOK (21 pts), and TOXICITY (20 pts) pair T with X for longer scoring words.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>T+Z combinations:</strong> TIZZY (26 pts), TOPAZ (16 pts), TZATZIKI (29 pts) — T with Z creates some of the highest-scoring T-words available. Always check for these when holding both tiles.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>TH- for reliable plays:</strong> THYME (13 pts), THWACK (18 pts), THYROID (14 pts) — TH words are abundant and accessible. They're your reliable scoring baseline when premium plays aren't available.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>TW- for board coverage:</strong> TWEEZING (21 pts), TWEEZERS (20 pts), TWELFTH (16 pts) — TW- words tend to be longer, spreading across the board to hit multiple premium squares.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Keep T for bingo potential:</strong> T appears in common bingo patterns (-TION, -TING, -MENT). If your rack has bingo potential, T is often the tile that completes it.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">The TH Digraph: T's Secret Weapon</h2>
      <p>TH is the most common consonant digraph in English. In Scrabble, having T and H together opens massive word options:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>THYME (13 pts):</strong> Five letters using the valuable Y tile — a reliable mid-scorer</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>THWACK (18 pts):</strong> Six letters using W and K — strong for a tile group without X or Z</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>THERAPY (15 pts):</strong> Seven letters — potential bingo if it's your full rack play</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Managing Multiple T Tiles</h2>
      <p>Drawing two T tiles is common and manageable — words like TWITTER, TATTERS, and TATTER exist. Three T tiles gets awkward but isn't an emergency. ATTEMPT and ATTEST use double-T effectively. If you draw four T tiles (rare but possible), exchange immediately — no rack can function with that many duplicate consonants.</p>
      <p>The key with duplicate T is to look for words with double-T patterns: -ETTE, -ATTER, -ITTER, -UTTER. These absorb both tiles while keeping your remaining rack balanced for the next draw.</p>

